\noindent Most of the ELG subsamples trace the {\hbox{Na\,{\sc i}\,D}}--Mg\,b relation of Equation~\ref{eqn:NaD} (shown as a dashed blue line on Fig.~\ref{fig:NaD}a). SPOGs* are the marked exception.  The {\hbox{Na\,{\sc i}\,D}}--Mg\,b relation in SPOGs* most closely resembles the relation in {\hbox{EW(H$\delta$)\,$>$\,5\AA}}\ objects, but only at the small {\hbox{Na\,{\sc i}\,D}}\ end.  SPOGs* have a substantial (and unique) tail into strong {\hbox{Na\,{\sc i}\,D}}\ absorption (compared to Mg\,b).  Figure\,\ref{fig:NaD_cdf} shows the probability distribution function (PDF; left) and the cumulative distribution function (CDF; right) of the {\hbox{Na\,{\sc i}\,D}}--Mg\,b relation, collapsed along the line described by Equation~\ref{eqn:NaD}. While most subsamples follow the same distribution around Equation~\ref{eqn:NaD}, SPOGs* show a deviation, evident in both the PDF and the CDF. A non-parametric Kolmogorov-Smirnov test\footnote{\href{http://idlastro.gsfc.nasa.gov/ftp/pro/math/kstwo.pro}{http://idlastro.gsfc.nasa.gov/ftp/pro/math/kstwo.pro}} was run to compare SPOGs* to the other distributions, with the null hypothesis being ruled out with a confidence {\em p}\,$\ll$\,0.001. In detail, 245 (23\%) SPOGs* are at least 1 standard deviation (1$\sigma$) above Equation~\ref{eqn:NaD}, 120 (11\%) at least 2$\sigma$, and 56 (5\%) SPOGs* exceed Equation~\ref{eqn:NaD} by at least 3$\sigma$, confirming that a substantial population of SPOGs* show significant {\hbox{Na\,{\sc i}\,D}}\ enhancement above what is expected from stellar contributions based on Mg\,b absorption.



Enhanced {\hbox{Na\,{\sc i}\,D}}\ absorption has been shown to be a signature of neutral winds \citep{rupke+05}. It is possible that other subsamples may too host winds (such as the star-forming subsample; \citealt{sarzi+16}). Given the enhancement in {\hbox{Na\,{\sc i}\,D}}\ absorption over Mg\,b, SPOGs* may have proportionally more interstellar neutral material as a population than the other subsamples.  Additionally, given the masses and A-star populations seen in SPOGs*, the enhanced {\hbox{Na\,{\sc i}\,D}}\ is much more likely to be due to interstellar winds.  {\hbox{Na\,{\sc i}\,D}}\ winds found in AGN-driven molecular outflows, such as Markarian\,231 \citep{rupke+11} and NGC\,1266 \citep{davis+12} were concentrated in the center, and traced the molecular outflow from the AGN. The velocity dynamics in both these systems made it clear that this absorption is due to the AGN-driven neutral wind.  Given that the discovery of NGC\,1266 was the catalyst for the SPOG survey, finding that SPOGs* as a population also have {\hbox{Na\,{\sc i}\,D}}\ absorption enhanced beyond what standard stellar population models predict is promising, and is a sign that our selection criteria have indeed produced the special population of transitioning galaxies that we were looking for.  


This shows that SPOGs* satisfying our {\hbox{EW(H$\delta$)\,$>$\,5\AA}}\ and shock criteria are not a random subsample of ELGs; they have distinct {\hbox{Na\,{\sc i}\,D}}\ behavior, showing a large wing with enhanced {\hbox{Na\,{\sc i}\,D}}\ absorption. In starbursts, these neutral winds tend to be attributed to stellar feedback, but given that the SPOGs* selection actively excludes star formation, the enhanced {\hbox{Na\,{\sc i}\,D}}\ absorption is likely from another source, such as AGN feedback. One potential caveat is that a {\hbox{Na\,{\sc i}\,D}}\ enhancement alone is not sufficient to confirm the presence of neutral winds, as enhanced {\hbox{Na\,{\sc i}\,D}}\ can also come from tidal debris sitting in front of the stars. Thus, an in-depth study of the kinematics and extent of the {\hbox{Na\,{\sc i}\,D}}\ absorption is necessary to determine the mass output and to confirm whether the {\hbox{Na\,{\sc i}\,D}}\ in SPOGs* is due to interstellar winds. A full investigation of the {\hbox{Na\,{\sc i}\,D}}\ properties of SPOGs* will be presented in a future paper.


