\begin{appendix}
\section{Investigating the potential biases for the ELG and SPOGs}
\label{app:bias}

With the ability to study millions of galaxies over cosmic time, astronomers using SDSS data have transformed the study of galaxy evolution. However, despite this success, fiber spectroscopy suffers from a major drawback: for nearby galaxies, a fiber is only able to target its center.  Within the OSSY sample, the size of the 3$''$ SDSS fiber varies in physical scale upon the galaxy by over two orders of magnitude, based on the redshift that is being investigated. For this reason, we must discuss possible aperture effects that are present in both the ELG and the SPOG* sample. First, we explored whether the emission line selection criterion (and thus the relative fractions of diagnostic classifications) was biased by redshift, due to requiring the detection of a weak line ({\hbox{[O\,{\sc i}]}}). Our {\hbox{[O\,{\sc i}]}}\ criterion resulted in a slight preferential exclusion of LINERs, however this bias does not appear to be significant.

\citet{kewley+05} investigated aperture biases in-depth in the context of both the SDSS and the Nearby Field Galaxy Survey (NFGS), and found that when calculating metallicity, star formation rates, and extinction, the aperture bias could play a significant role if $<$\,20\% of the total galaxy light made it down the fiber. In the case of the ELG and SPOGs, we are not attempting to infer global properties of the galaxies, but rather simply classifying them. When \citet{kewley+05} investigated whether the objects in the NFGS (with a 2$''$ fiber) would change their line diagnostic classifications when comparing the nuclear emission lines to the integrated, only 2/115 (1.7\%) were found to change. In fact, \citet{lamassa+12} investigated how many objects were found to be misclassified AGNs in SDSS below {\em z}\,$<$\,0.3, and found that this effect was negligible. Thus it is unlikely that our sample has strong aperture biases in the {\em spectral} classification of the galaxies.  

On the other hand, the small central aperture did find objects classified as SPOGs* that had extended star formation (see \S\ref{sec:sf_contaminants}). To investigate the magnitude of this issue, we plotted the {\hbox{EW(H$\delta$)\,$>$\,5\AA}}\ and SPOG* detection rate as a function of $M_r$ and redshift, shown in Figure \ref{fig:mass_z} (note: Figure~\ref{fig:Mr_z} shows that small $M_r$, high redshift objects are not found in the ELG). The identification fraction of {\hbox{EW(H$\delta$)\,$>$\,5\AA}}\ objects strongly depends both on $M_r$ and redshift, with large $M_r$ objects being less likely to have strong Balmer absorption. At the smallest $M_r$, the {\hbox{EW(H$\delta$)\,$>$\,5\AA}}\ fraction decreases slightly with redshift, possibly due to a number of low mass dwarfs that fit the ELG criterion, but this trend reverses as $M_r$ grows larger, with increasing detection rates amongst the higher redshift ELG objects. It is very likely that this is due to the SDSS fiber picking up larger areas of the star-forming disk (as opposed to the bulge).

